                "question_type": "Comparative/Trend",
                "question": "Compare the mobility (\u03bc\ud835\udc39\ud835\udc38) trends in panels (e), (f), and (g). Which selective cation treatment best preserves the high mobility of the reference (Black line)?",
                "answer_type": "Paragraph",
                "answer": "Gallium oxide (IG*ZO). In panel (f), the mobility curve for the N\u2082O-treated sample (Red line) remains close to the reference, whereas Indium (panel e) and Zinc (panel g) treatments cause severe mobility degradation."
            },
            {
                "question_type": "Structure-Property",
                "question": "The \u201cI*GZO\u201d (Indium-treated) sample in panel (e) shows a drastic collapse in field-effect mobility. What functional role does Indium play in the IGZO lattice that explains this sensitivity?",
                "answer_type": "Paragraph",
                "answer": "Carrier conduction path. Indium 5s orbitals form the primary conduction band minimum. N\u2082O treatment during the Indium cycle disrupts orbital overlap or excessively reduces carrier density, leading to a collapse in electron mobility."
            }
        ],
        "f": [
            {
